\subsection{Processing residue rate}{

The rate is derived from FAO product composition of industrial roundwood
(from \code{f73_prod_specific_timber}, stable at these shares across 1965-2015)
and product-specific recovery rates:\tabular{lllll}{
   Product \tab Share of IR \tab Recovery \tab Residue rate \tab Source \cr
   Sawnwood (sawlogs + veneer) \tab ~57\% \tab 50\% \tab \strong{43\%} \tab FAO/UNECE; Mantau 2012 UNECE DP-51 \cr
   Pulpwood \tab ~35\% \tab 95-100\% \tab \strong{0-5\%} \tab Black liquor burned internally \cr
   Other industrial roundwood \tab ~8\% \tab ~50\% \tab \strong{43\%} \tab Assumed same as sawnwood \cr
}


Production-weighted rate: 0.57 x 0.43 + 0.35 x 0.025 + 0.08 x 0.43 = \strong{0.29}
Rounded to \strong{0.30} (stable at 30-35\% across 1965-2015 FAO data).
}

\subsection{Why only industrial roundwood, not woodfuel}{

Processing residues are computed from industrial roundwood supply (\code{ov_supply("wood")})
only. Woodfuel (\code{ov_supply("woodfuel")}) is excluded because it is burned directly
for energy — it does not pass through sawmills or pulp mills and therefore generates
no processing residues.
}

\subsection{Why all processing residues go to energy}{

In reality, some processing residues are used for pulp or particleboard. However,
MAgPIE models all wood products as aggregate "industrial roundwood" (\code{kforestry = wood}).
The downstream split into sawnwood, pulp, and panels is not modeled — there is no
competing use for processing residues within MAgPIE. Therefore, all processing
residues are assumed available for energy use.
}

\subsection{Construction wood}{

\code{calcConstructionWoodDemand} in mrcommons applies a factor 2 to construction wood demand,
reflecting a 50\% sawmill recovery rate (Churkina et al. 2020). This means half of the
harvested roundwood for construction becomes processing waste. These residues are clean,
uniform offcuts with high energy recovery potential. Reported separately from general
processing residues.
}

\subsection{What this function does NOT include}{
\itemize{
\item \strong{Logging residues} (branches, tops): already in MAgPIE woodfuel (\code{v73_prod_residues})
\item \strong{Post-consumer waste wood} (demolition, furniture): excluded for consistency with
\code{carbonLTS}, which tracks CO2 from HWP decay using IPCC first-order decay (half-lives:
sawnwood 30yr, construction 60yr, pulpwood 2yr). Adding end-of-life energy recovery
would require splitting HWP outflow into burned vs decayed fractions — assumptions
not currently in the model. The CO2 from HWP decay is already reported; the energy
from burning waste wood is not tracked to avoid parallel lifetime assumptions.
\item \strong{Black liquor}: burned internally at pulp mills, not available for external energy
}
}

